        <abstract> 
<p>CD is mistaken in considering <hi rend="italic">Acropera</hi> unisexual, with only male flowers [<hi rend="italic">Orchids</hi>, pp. 203–10]. JS has successfully fertilised two <hi rend="italic">A. loddigesii</hi> flowers. One is ripening. Dissection of the other shows the pollen accomplishes fertilisation without contacting any stigmatic surface. Abortive ovules found in flowers that did not become fertilised when pollinated. JS suggests <hi rend="italic">Acropera</hi> has both unisexual male and hermaphrodite flowers.</p> 
        </abstract>
